WEBVTT

00:18.059 --> 00:20.061
curious music

00:48.256 --> 00:49.591
Well, I know my wife's been

00:49.632 --> 00:51.051
looking around
         for something special.

00:51.092 --> 00:52.552
After all, it's been

00:52.594 --> 00:54.095
a few years
    since I bought her a diamond.

00:54.137 --> 00:56.097
This is a half hoop.

00:56.139 --> 00:57.932
Of course, the diamond content
          in the full hoop

00:57.974 --> 00:59.184
is much greater.

00:59.225 --> 01:01.686
Was it a half hoop
             or a full hoop

01:01.728 --> 01:03.521
your wife had in mind?

01:04.105 --> 01:07.567
I think she'd prefer
             the full hoop.

01:07.609 --> 01:09.194
Most women do.

01:11.237 --> 01:12.947
Mary, have you seen these?

01:12.989 --> 01:16.117
Jane, those are diamonds.

01:16.159 --> 01:19.287
I know. Aren't they gorgeous?

01:19.329 --> 01:21.748
And it is your birthday
             quite soon.

01:21.790 --> 01:23.458
Well...

01:23.958 --> 01:26.086
It's always worth
       showing an expensive piece

01:26.127 --> 01:27.462
from the top end

01:27.504 --> 01:29.297
even if it doesn't sell
             for some time.

01:29.339 --> 01:31.299
You know, what you might call
       an aspirational piece.

01:31.341 --> 01:33.301
Uh, so what's the point
        of attracting people

01:33.343 --> 01:35.428
with an item
      they can't afford to buy?

01:35.470 --> 01:38.139
Because they'll tend to spend
 more on what they choose to buy.

01:45.647 --> 01:47.607
Well, this is the one I like,

01:47.649 --> 01:50.693
but why is it nearly twice
         the price of this one?

01:51.402 --> 01:54.531
The value of a diamond
 depends on four characteristics.

01:54.572 --> 01:56.157
The larger the diamond,

01:56.199 --> 01:58.034
the rarer it is,
        the better the color,

01:58.076 --> 01:59.577
the more valuable it is.

01:59.619 --> 02:02.497
The greater the clarity,
       the more beautiful it is.

02:04.415 --> 02:06.000
However,
     it's the quality of the cut

02:06.042 --> 02:07.544
that gives the diamond
           its brilliance.

02:08.169 --> 02:10.755
-  What about that one?
     -  A very fine stone.

02:10.797 --> 02:12.465
Remarkably few inclusions.

02:12.507 --> 02:15.510
Yes, well, internal
        characteristics are only

02:15.552 --> 02:17.178
really visible
         through the loupe.

02:17.220 --> 02:18.847
Beautiful clarity.

02:24.227 --> 02:25.687
And, of course,

02:25.728 --> 02:27.814
you don't see
      the high dispersion you get

02:27.856 --> 02:29.774
with simulated stones.

02:29.816 --> 02:31.276
It is a diamond, then?

02:48.126 --> 02:49.919
atmospheric music

03:16.863 --> 03:19.741
I like so much idea
       about synthetic diamonds.

03:20.783 --> 03:23.745
It is much more cheaper
          than natural stones.

03:24.537 --> 03:27.498
And also, they looks better.

03:30.251 --> 03:35.215
But if a diamond
 can be produced in a laboratory,

03:35.256 --> 03:37.759
of the same or better quality,

03:37.800 --> 03:39.260
for much, much cheaper,

03:39.302 --> 03:42.263
why should we still
         mine for diamonds?

03:46.851 --> 03:48.478
Uh, that's...

03:48.519 --> 03:51.439
I can tell you only this is
      a good question. 

03:52.815 --> 03:57.612
Some people want something that
      really belongs to the earth,

03:57.654 --> 04:00.323
something what is made by God,

04:00.365 --> 04:04.244
not made in the... some lab.

04:04.285 --> 04:06.579
What do you think about this?

04:13.711 --> 04:15.463
dramatic music

04:21.010 --> 04:23.221
Let me tell you a story, right?

04:23.263 --> 04:25.473
When I started
    in the diamond business, um,

04:25.515 --> 04:27.934
and I was knocking on doors,

04:27.976 --> 04:30.645
my mother gave me $5,000 cash.

04:30.687 --> 04:32.647
I said, "Mom, I don't want
        to take your money."

04:32.689 --> 04:34.607
She says, "I don't want you
         to spend the money.

04:34.649 --> 04:36.442
I want you to put it
           in your pocket.

04:36.484 --> 04:38.152
You'll talk differently
             if you have

04:38.194 --> 04:40.238
$5,000 in your pocket."

04:40.280 --> 04:42.573
That's what she said to me.

04:42.615 --> 04:45.660
You wear something
           that's valuable

04:45.702 --> 04:49.622
and you know it's valuable,
       you strut differently.

04:49.664 --> 04:51.082
You feel different.

04:51.124 --> 04:53.167
Your sense of confidence,
     your sense of who you are,

04:53.209 --> 04:54.377
is different.

04:54.419 --> 04:57.839
The real thing has...

04:57.880 --> 05:00.800
brings with it a certain sense
       of "I know it's real."

05:00.842 --> 05:04.679
You could have a Picasso
           in your house--

05:04.721 --> 05:07.056
it's a lithograph,

05:07.098 --> 05:10.059
and maybe no one knows that
      it's not the real thing,

05:10.101 --> 05:12.312
but you do.

05:14.063 --> 05:15.565
When I tell people

05:15.606 --> 05:17.233
I'm gonna sit down
        with Martin Rapaport,

05:17.275 --> 05:18.901
what I usually say is,

05:18.943 --> 05:20.278
"This is the most famous person
      in the diamond industry.

05:20.320 --> 05:21.779
He sets the prices of diamonds."

05:21.821 --> 05:23.823
Oh, I don't set the prices.
        I report the prices.

05:23.865 --> 05:26.075
It's like the weatherman.
      I don't make the weather.

05:26.117 --> 05:28.703
I let you know
        what the weather is.

05:30.705 --> 05:32.373
-No.
                -Why?

05:33.207 --> 05:34.959
Because I don't think that...

05:35.001 --> 05:37.211
I don't legitimize a product
   that I believe is gonna be seen

05:37.253 --> 05:41.215
as one of the most illegitimate
    products in the 21st century.

05:44.927 --> 05:47.055
-When was 9/11?
               -2001.

05:47.096 --> 05:49.640
Yeah. So, in 2003,

05:49.682 --> 05:53.478
I made a conference in New York
       about synthetic diamonds.

05:53.519 --> 05:55.563
This is what the,
       uh, machine looks like.

05:55.605 --> 05:58.524
And when we apply the pressure
         and the temperature

05:58.566 --> 06:00.735
to this core, the... Whoa!

06:00.777 --> 06:02.987
Synthetic diamonds
           were not that new,

06:03.029 --> 06:04.489
but the ability to create

06:04.530 --> 06:07.658
gem-quality
        synthetic diamonds was.

06:07.700 --> 06:10.536
Visually, even to the most
       experienced gemologist,

06:10.578 --> 06:13.873
they may be indistinguishable
        from natural diamond.

06:16.376 --> 06:18.211
It's a big problem for all of us

06:18.252 --> 06:20.380
because it's already
           on the market.

06:20.421 --> 06:22.256
It's already here.

06:22.298 --> 06:24.300
What are we going to do?

06:25.134 --> 06:26.844
A synthetic diamond

06:26.886 --> 06:29.597
will be produced
    and reproduced with machines

06:29.639 --> 06:32.725
until supply exceeds demand.

06:32.767 --> 06:35.228
The consumer is used to
          having technology

06:35.269 --> 06:38.356
bring them products
   they otherwise couldn't afford.

06:38.398 --> 06:40.066
Simple as that.

06:40.108 --> 06:41.776
A diamond is a diamond.

06:41.818 --> 06:43.945
Are you crazy?
     The wedding ring is a sign

06:43.986 --> 06:45.530
of ultimate commitment and love,

06:45.571 --> 06:47.448
and the woman doesn't
       just think it's worth,

06:47.490 --> 06:48.950
I don't know, $80 or 120...

06:48.991 --> 06:51.452
"Put it on a scale,
      and that's our marriage."

06:51.494 --> 06:53.538
No, no, no, not at all.

06:53.579 --> 06:57.458
The diamond's actually
       a symbol of commitment.

06:57.500 --> 06:59.293
It has to be expensive.

06:59.335 --> 07:01.254
It has to have value.
        Has to retain value.

07:01.295 --> 07:04.841
The woman projects
      the value of the diamond

07:04.882 --> 07:06.843
onto herself.

07:06.884 --> 07:09.178
"He's giving me something
           of great value

07:09.220 --> 07:12.098
because he values me greatly."

07:12.140 --> 07:15.935
He thinks she thinks,
    "Oh, this is like a diamond.

07:15.977 --> 07:19.063
I just got a better deal
       'cause it's man-made."

07:19.105 --> 07:20.606
They're suckers.

07:20.648 --> 07:22.692
Because eventually,
       what's going to happen?

07:22.733 --> 07:24.277
They're gonna come back
            in ten years,

07:24.318 --> 07:27.238
and they'll say,
        "Oh, what's it worth?

07:27.280 --> 07:29.532
What's my marriage worth?

07:29.574 --> 07:31.951
What's my relationship worth?"

07:32.952 --> 07:35.872
dramatic music

07:35.913 --> 07:38.458
I just think the idea of

07:38.499 --> 07:42.837
"is it real or isn't it real"
             is so absurd.

07:42.879 --> 07:45.131
I was at a birthday party
               in Paris,

07:45.173 --> 07:48.676
and the woman sitting next me,
       she smiled and said, "So,

07:48.718 --> 07:50.178
what kind of jewelry
           do you design?"

07:50.219 --> 07:54.599
I was like, "Um, well,
     actually, I designed that.

07:54.640 --> 07:56.684
I designed
       your engagement ring."

07:56.726 --> 07:59.479
And she said,
   "You design engagement rings?"

07:59.520 --> 08:03.649
And I said, "No, I designed
       your engagement ring."

08:04.901 --> 08:08.488
And her husband immediately
       asked me what all men ask.

08:08.529 --> 08:10.281
They ask about the price.

08:10.323 --> 08:11.657
"Tell me the truth.

08:11.699 --> 08:13.367
Well, how much
        should it have cost?"

08:13.409 --> 08:15.328
He just kept saying,
        "Tell me the truth."

08:15.369 --> 08:18.164
And I said, "You want the truth?
   Do you want to know the truth?

08:18.206 --> 08:20.458
The truth about diamonds is
    they're all exactly the same

08:20.500 --> 08:22.710
and none of them are
       really worth anything."

08:22.752 --> 08:24.378
And then, ultimately,
             I was like,

08:24.420 --> 08:26.672
"Do you know what
        a diamond cartel is?"

08:29.300 --> 08:31.427
Mm-hmm.

08:31.469 --> 08:33.429
People want a variety of things.

08:33.471 --> 08:35.139
None of them are particularly

08:35.181 --> 08:38.601
about romance or true love.

08:38.643 --> 08:40.269
suspenseful music

08:41.354 --> 08:42.813
People want things

08:42.855 --> 08:45.691
because they've been told
             to want them.

08:45.733 --> 08:48.236
And De Beers has convinced

08:48.277 --> 08:51.822
hundreds of millions of people
         over almost a century

08:51.864 --> 08:55.910
so effectively
       that they want a diamond.

08:55.952 --> 08:59.413
And the way they did it
      was by inventing a product--

08:59.455 --> 09:01.499
they called it
          an engagement ring--

09:01.541 --> 09:03.960
that would hold these
         little white diamonds,

09:04.001 --> 09:06.170
which were
       the least desirable kind.

09:06.212 --> 09:07.338
But before that,

09:07.380 --> 09:08.673
nobody really wanted them,

09:08.714 --> 09:10.466
and this was just a way to get

09:10.508 --> 09:13.094
the new emerging middle class
               of America

09:13.135 --> 09:15.304
after World War II to buy them.

09:15.346 --> 09:17.265
So, what is a diamond?

09:17.306 --> 09:18.641
What's a stone worth?

09:18.683 --> 09:20.226
Why do people want
            what they want?

09:20.268 --> 09:22.812
And in this case,

09:22.853 --> 09:26.440
the answer is:
    because they've been told to.

09:26.482 --> 09:27.692
That must've set you back a bit.

09:27.733 --> 09:29.735
Not really.
      About two months' salary.

09:29.777 --> 09:31.904
Not much for something
           that's forever.

09:31.946 --> 09:34.490
A diamond is forever.

09:35.283 --> 09:36.742
De Beers invented

09:36.784 --> 09:38.619
a way to sell them to people.

09:38.661 --> 09:43.207
People want the thing,
            the best thing,

09:43.249 --> 09:45.543
and they've convinced them
        that that's a diamond

09:45.585 --> 09:48.629
and nothing else.

09:50.590 --> 09:53.217
De Beers is
         the diamond business,

09:53.259 --> 09:55.469
and this building is
           where they control

09:55.511 --> 09:57.471
the world diamond trade.

09:58.139 --> 10:00.766
curious music

10:00.808 --> 10:03.978
By buying up most of
      the world's uncut diamonds,

10:04.020 --> 10:07.815
the company can regulate supply
          to select dealers...

10:09.191 --> 10:12.612
...increasing it in good years
         and reducing it in bad

10:12.653 --> 10:14.989
to keep prices high.

10:15.031 --> 10:17.825
A century after it began,

10:17.867 --> 10:21.120
the diamond cartel
     still controls the production,

10:21.162 --> 10:24.332
the marketing and the pricing of
 rough diamonds around the world.

10:24.373 --> 10:26.083
It's impossible to say

10:26.125 --> 10:30.504
factual statements about
    De Beers without sounding...

10:32.214 --> 10:34.467
...judgmental.

10:34.508 --> 10:36.677
Its monopolistic control

10:36.719 --> 10:38.346
violates U.S. antitrust laws,

10:38.387 --> 10:42.016
but the cartel has successfully
          kept its executives

10:42.058 --> 10:43.851
beyond the reach
          of American justice.

10:43.893 --> 10:45.519
Well, until there's

10:45.561 --> 10:48.522
a major crack in the market,
       the cartel will survive

10:48.564 --> 10:50.983
simply because
          it is too powerful.

10:51.025 --> 10:52.818
And that's fine,
            because it's not

10:52.860 --> 10:55.154
about anything important;
        it's about diamonds.

10:55.196 --> 10:57.531
De Beers executives are nervous
         about all of this.

10:57.573 --> 10:58.908
They would not allow themselves

10:58.949 --> 11:00.368
to be interviewed
            for   60 Minutes.

11:00.409 --> 11:02.036
Then again,

11:02.078 --> 11:03.871
it's very important
     because it's moved capital

11:03.913 --> 11:06.749
across continents
        for about 100 years.

11:22.390 --> 11:25.351
"Serena e Lomunno"
           by Riz Ortolani

11:31.941 --> 11:33.567
History has always been

11:33.609 --> 11:35.736
part of the diamond world.

11:35.778 --> 11:37.029
The generation

11:37.071 --> 11:38.906
that preceded me within De Beers

11:38.948 --> 11:41.409
who would've, you know,
       locked the front door,

11:41.450 --> 11:43.244
and nobody in, thank you.

11:43.285 --> 11:45.079
This interview
      would not have happened.

11:45.121 --> 11:46.831
No, I don't think so.

11:48.457 --> 11:51.544
De Beers was controlled by
     the Oppenheimers since really

11:51.585 --> 11:53.254
sort of the 1920s.

11:53.295 --> 11:57.049
But they're all gone,
      and, well, I'm still there,

11:57.091 --> 11:58.843
so I carry on with the mission.

12:01.429 --> 12:06.267
Yeah, you know,
    it helps in life to be lucky.

12:06.809 --> 12:09.603
There must have been
           something ordained

12:09.645 --> 12:11.897
in the way I ended up.

12:11.939 --> 12:13.274
Some say, "What's your job,
           then, Stephen?"

12:13.315 --> 12:15.109
Oh, well, you know,
       in a way, my job is to

12:15.151 --> 12:18.070
inspire, I guess,
            each generation

12:18.112 --> 12:22.366
with this extraordinary story
            of the diamond.

12:22.408 --> 12:23.951
People don't know, huh,

12:23.993 --> 12:26.412
a diamond is like
        three billion years old.

12:26.454 --> 12:27.955
Older than life.

12:28.914 --> 12:31.959
Some of them older
       than stars in the sky.

12:34.795 --> 12:36.797
You can't make that.

12:36.839 --> 12:39.258
Yeah, we can synthesize carbon,

12:39.300 --> 12:42.303
but in reality,
 we can't make what a diamond is.

12:42.344 --> 12:45.014
We can't make something
      which is a billion years old

12:45.055 --> 12:47.641
that connects us
   to the formation of the world.

12:47.683 --> 12:51.812
We can't make something where
 every one is inherently unique.

12:51.854 --> 12:55.816
And we can't make something
      that has an intrinsic rarity

12:55.858 --> 12:57.818
and preciousness to it.

12:57.860 --> 12:59.695
And the one thing that

12:59.737 --> 13:02.281
waried us a lot about
         lab-grown diamonds

13:02.323 --> 13:05.659
is if they were marketed
       in a way that pretended

13:05.701 --> 13:08.788
that they had the values
         of a real diamond.

13:10.873 --> 13:13.793
playful music

13:16.212 --> 13:19.256
We're in the period
           of misinformation.

13:19.298 --> 13:20.966
Well, confusion.

13:21.008 --> 13:23.344
People aren't quite sure
    what it is or what it isn't,

13:23.385 --> 13:27.264
but, um, it's only
        an existential threat

13:27.306 --> 13:31.268
if-if we somehow damage
          the relationship

13:31.310 --> 13:34.772
that consumers have
