15:05.362 --> 15:07.531
And then,
     like a couple years later,

15:07.573 --> 15:09.909
somebody comes up with a process
      to mass-produce aluminum,

15:09.950 --> 15:11.702
and now it's dirt cheap.

15:11.744 --> 15:16.040
So, what was once, you know,
      really coveted and valuable

15:16.081 --> 15:19.293
is just a commodity
         that we throw away.

15:19.335 --> 15:21.420
You know, diamond's
         gonna be the same.

15:22.546 --> 15:25.174
John Janik,
        he is a Carnegie fellow

15:25.215 --> 15:27.468
from the Carnegie Institution.

15:27.509 --> 15:30.930
Okay, so here you have these,
       um, synthetic diamonds.

15:30.971 --> 15:33.140
-Mm-hmm.
      -And you actually, uh...

15:33.182 --> 15:34.975
you like to call them
         cultured diamonds.

15:35.017 --> 15:36.435
You took them
      to the Diamond District--

15:36.477 --> 15:38.395
the real one--
       not too far from here,

15:38.437 --> 15:40.272
and they couldn't tell
           the difference.

15:40.314 --> 15:42.232
- Not-not... not a bit.
             -Not a bit.

15:42.274 --> 15:44.109
And they appraised them
            for basically

15:44.151 --> 15:45.778
what natural diamonds
            would go for?

15:45.819 --> 15:47.488
That's right--
        for wholesale prices.

15:47.529 --> 15:51.241
My PhD was in making crystals
       of different materials.

15:51.825 --> 15:54.995
I would make rubies,
        which is aluminum oxide

15:55.037 --> 15:57.957
with a little bit
           of chromium in it.

15:57.998 --> 16:01.085
I made exotic uranium compounds.

16:01.126 --> 16:02.920
I made these materials,
            and then I went

16:02.962 --> 16:04.505
and studied their properties.

16:04.546 --> 16:09.343
A crystal is just
 a repeating structure of atoms.

16:09.385 --> 16:12.596
So, if you have a carbon
      and a carbon and a carbon

16:12.638 --> 16:15.641
in a repeating pattern,
      that's a diamond crystal.

16:15.683 --> 16:17.893
We can actually make diamonds
        that are more perfect

16:17.935 --> 16:19.228
than natural diamonds.

16:19.269 --> 16:21.188
We can grow
       about a carat per day.

16:21.230 --> 16:22.815
But it will be cheaper, though.

16:22.856 --> 16:24.733
-That's the whole point.
   -You can't tell the difference.

16:24.775 --> 16:27.444
So, if you can't tell
   the difference, John, then this

16:27.486 --> 16:30.447
inevitably has to hurt
    the diamond market out there.

16:30.489 --> 16:32.241
You mean these things
          have value? I...

16:32.282 --> 16:34.410
-I had no idea.

16:41.000 --> 16:42.793
You got to understand,

16:42.835 --> 16:46.880
the sale of synthetic diamonds
     as diamond engagement rings

16:46.922 --> 16:49.717
is a fundamental violation
            of the ethics

16:49.758 --> 16:51.385
of the diamond industry,
           in my opinion.

16:51.427 --> 16:53.012
But is-is it
        just about the money?

16:53.053 --> 16:54.346
'Cause, you know, that's...

16:54.388 --> 16:56.890
You-you're hurting people
          where it counts.

16:56.932 --> 16:59.893
You're kicking them
         in their emotional,

16:59.935 --> 17:02.938
"I love you," commitment spot.

17:02.980 --> 17:04.898
This is terrible,
         terrible, terrible!

17:04.940 --> 17:06.567
I mean, come on.

17:06.608 --> 17:09.194
If I want to rip you off,
          fine, rip me off.

17:09.236 --> 17:12.489
Why rip me off
      with what I gave my wife?

17:12.531 --> 17:16.452
There's a story of a guy who was
     selling treated diamonds--

17:16.493 --> 17:18.203
it's called
       the Yehuda treatment--

17:18.245 --> 17:20.748
but he charged everyone
            a-a lot less.

17:20.789 --> 17:22.666
suspenseful music

17:22.708 --> 17:24.918
But when the women found out

17:24.960 --> 17:27.671
that their diamonds
            were treated,

17:27.713 --> 17:30.132
there was a line
          around the block

17:30.174 --> 17:32.801
and around the block
        and around the block

17:32.843 --> 17:34.636
to try to return the diamonds.

17:34.678 --> 17:38.098
The women, they felt
      so cheated and so angry,

17:38.140 --> 17:42.561
and this guy, he gave everybody
   the money till he had no money.

17:42.603 --> 17:45.189
Then he drank jewelry cleaner
         and killed himself.

17:49.568 --> 17:52.279
And he didn't steal... he didn't
     rip 'em off, theoretically.

17:52.321 --> 17:53.781
It wasn't about the money.

17:53.822 --> 17:55.365
It was the failure
           to disclose it.

17:55.407 --> 17:57.034
Look, I don't know
        what's gonna happen.

17:57.076 --> 17:58.911
Right?
     But in ten years from now,

17:58.952 --> 18:00.412
there's an extremely great
             likelihood

18:00.454 --> 18:02.623
that people are gonna
         look back and say,

18:02.664 --> 18:04.583
"That diamond industry!

18:04.625 --> 18:06.919
They sold that stuff!

18:06.960 --> 18:09.630
And it wasn't worth
      the price I paid at all!

18:09.671 --> 18:10.756
What did they do to me?"

18:10.798 --> 18:12.132
And how is the woman gonna feel

18:12.174 --> 18:14.009
if she projects the value
           of the diamond

18:14.051 --> 18:15.469
onto herself subconsciously?

18:15.511 --> 18:17.805
How is she gonna feel
         about her diamond?

18:17.846 --> 18:19.973
intriguing music

18:20.015 --> 18:22.601
Let's say someone sees my ring

18:22.643 --> 18:24.728
and says, "Is that real?"

18:24.770 --> 18:25.896
Am I gonna say

18:25.938 --> 18:27.523
yes or no?

18:30.609 --> 18:32.945
No woman who thought
     she could get away with it

18:32.986 --> 18:37.449
has ever, ever said,
          "No, it's fake."

18:41.036 --> 18:44.289
Okay, but is
        a diamond a diamond?

18:44.331 --> 18:46.208
What do you mean?

18:46.250 --> 18:48.168
I mean synthetic diamonds

18:48.210 --> 18:50.295
have leaked into
      the natural diamond market.

18:50.337 --> 18:52.089
Really?

18:52.131 --> 18:54.007
There saying one percent, maybe,

18:54.049 --> 18:55.467
in the form of melee--

18:55.509 --> 18:57.177
these teeny, teeny,
            tiny diamonds

18:57.219 --> 18:58.846
that are sold in parcels.

18:58.887 --> 19:00.305
It's more like 20%.

19:00.347 --> 19:02.891
And nobody's even saying
              what percent

19:02.933 --> 19:05.144
of larger stones are lab-grown.

19:09.731 --> 19:12.067
But for the diamond,
   not for the synthetic diamond.

19:12.109 --> 19:14.069
The diamond was never real,
               either.

19:14.111 --> 19:16.530
The diamond was always a lie.

19:16.572 --> 19:19.575
So the synthetic diamond
     is just a lie about a lie,

19:19.616 --> 19:23.662
which I happen to think
            is hilarious

19:23.704 --> 19:25.873
and sort of delightful.

19:27.124 --> 19:28.792
And one could argue
        that synthetic diamonds,

19:28.834 --> 19:30.627
if what you're looking for is

19:30.669 --> 19:33.714
a really colorless,
      flawless one-- no nitrogen,

19:33.755 --> 19:37.759
no nothing-- they can be made

19:37.801 --> 19:41.680
like nature intended
      but never quite managed.

20:06.622 --> 20:08.415
tense music

20:44.868 --> 20:46.370
Every stone.

20:54.002 --> 20:56.421
Yeah. Yeah.

21:03.595 --> 21:05.389
This is really a problem,
              you know?

21:17.192 --> 21:19.486
Two, three months before this,

21:19.528 --> 21:23.949
we publish that we found like
     five percent stones mixed,

21:23.991 --> 21:26.159
you know, so...

21:30.038 --> 21:32.916
They would say,
           "If De Beers says,

21:32.958 --> 21:36.503
'In the thousands of the stones,
     we didn't found one stone,'

21:36.545 --> 21:40.841
then... the synthetics
         is not a problem."

21:40.882 --> 21:44.219
Like, uh, "It doesn't matter."

21:57.024 --> 21:59.192
So, where are those stones?

