No one will say, "I'm mixing
    and I'm selling," of course.

22:51.495 --> 22:54.373
No one told me this,
      but then they are saying,

22:54.414 --> 22:56.375
"Everybody are mixing

22:56.416 --> 22:59.211
if they can get the stones
              from China."

23:13.892 --> 23:15.685
dramatic music

24:57.913 --> 25:01.708
- Wow. Wow.

25:01.750 --> 25:04.419
Mm-hmm. Okay.

25:14.095 --> 25:15.430
At the beginning,

25:15.472 --> 25:18.141
the quality was, uh...

25:18.183 --> 25:20.018
was, uh, problematic.

25:36.952 --> 25:39.037
Who is, who is buying
            these stones?

25:39.079 --> 25:41.414
Where they are
        selling these stones?

26:32.382 --> 26:35.427
Look, we don't really
           sell diamonds.

26:35.468 --> 26:38.138
We sell the idea
        behind the diamonds.

26:38.179 --> 26:40.265
And what's going on
     with these synthetic guys,

26:40.307 --> 26:44.144
th-they're like parasites
       getting under our skin,

26:44.185 --> 26:45.895
and they're trying to steal
         the diamond dream.

26:45.937 --> 26:47.647
That's what they're really
            trying to do.

26:47.689 --> 26:49.733
They're trying
     to steal the diamond dream.

26:49.774 --> 26:52.485
But if they steal
         the diamond dream,

26:52.527 --> 26:55.572
if they burn the diamonds
          down to the core,

26:55.614 --> 26:58.158
if they destroy
       the basic customer base

26:58.199 --> 26:59.993
for buying diamonds

27:00.035 --> 27:02.912
as the ultimate symbol
         of committed love,

27:02.954 --> 27:05.373
now they've destroyed
           the whole idea.

27:05.415 --> 27:08.668
And that's the challenge that
 we face in the diamond industry.

27:13.214 --> 27:14.591
A young girl...

27:17.886 --> 27:20.263
...thinks about life

27:20.305 --> 27:23.266
and her future and what's
        going to happen to her.

27:23.308 --> 27:28.355
And she imagines one day
         she will fall in love.

27:29.147 --> 27:30.565
And she'll get married.

27:30.607 --> 27:34.527
And that person
        will give her a diamond.

27:34.569 --> 27:36.279
And so the diamond dream
               is about:

27:36.321 --> 27:39.407
What will life bring me?

27:39.449 --> 27:41.618
What greatness? What happiness?

27:41.660 --> 27:43.703
What's gonna happen to me?

27:43.745 --> 27:46.623
As a ten-year-old girl, even.

27:48.875 --> 27:51.836
The diamond dream
        is about relationships.

27:51.878 --> 27:55.548
The human condition
       is about relationships.

27:55.590 --> 27:58.968
We don't want to die alone.

28:04.015 --> 28:06.351
I think the diamond...
    you know, the-the words, huh,

28:06.393 --> 28:09.854
"a diamond dream," um,

28:09.896 --> 28:12.399
were probably something
       I just thought up, huh?

28:13.400 --> 28:15.360
playful music

28:19.989 --> 28:22.534
But actually, it existed
         long before De Beers.

28:22.575 --> 28:25.954
You know, it goes well back
        to the Duke of Burgundy,

28:25.995 --> 28:27.997
apparently, according to legend,

28:28.039 --> 28:31.501
who gave the first
        diamond betrothal ring.

28:31.543 --> 28:35.004
No marketer told him
             to do so, huh?

28:35.046 --> 28:38.341
And that core reason he did it
          is as true today

28:38.383 --> 28:40.510
as it was then, which is that

28:40.552 --> 28:45.473
he was seeking to send
     this symbol to his future wife

28:45.515 --> 28:47.767
that she was precious to him

28:47.809 --> 28:50.186
and that this moment
       that they were marking

28:50.228 --> 28:51.604
was something precious.

28:51.646 --> 28:53.106
No, because diamond cutting

28:53.148 --> 28:55.108
had just been perfected
              in Bruges

28:55.150 --> 28:58.528
and he wanted Bruges as part
    of a multinational land deal

28:58.570 --> 29:01.656
that involved marrying
          Mary of Burgundy.

29:01.698 --> 29:03.450
God, I wish people in history

29:03.491 --> 29:05.827
were named something
          other than Mary.

29:05.869 --> 29:08.872
And I would assume
       he knows that-- maybe--

29:08.913 --> 29:12.208
but, no, it wasn't 'cause
      it was a precious object.

29:12.250 --> 29:14.335
It was a token, for sure.

29:14.377 --> 29:17.839
And he didn't give it to her;
      he gave it to her father.

29:17.881 --> 29:19.758
And-and the point being?

29:19.799 --> 29:23.136
The point being
      that that story is bunk.

29:23.178 --> 29:24.679
Or...

29:24.721 --> 29:26.306
it's what you make out of it.

29:26.347 --> 29:27.724
It's kind of like a diamond.

29:27.766 --> 29:29.809
It's an ugly rock
       that if you cut enough

29:29.851 --> 29:31.644
reflective windows into it,

29:31.686 --> 29:34.439
it looks like something else.

29:34.481 --> 29:37.525
The 92-carat D color flawless,

29:37.567 --> 29:39.486
heart-shaped diamond and pearl,

29:39.527 --> 29:41.821
the largest
       D color flawless heart

29:41.863 --> 29:43.239
to be offered for sale
            at auction...

29:43.281 --> 29:46.159
Like, those large diamonds,

29:46.201 --> 29:48.745
those famous diamonds,

29:48.787 --> 29:51.539
they act like it's
     a once-in-a-lifetime find,

29:51.581 --> 29:53.500
and yet, every time you look,

29:53.541 --> 29:58.338
Sotheby's or Christie's
       is auctioning another one.

29:58.379 --> 30:01.966
It's the largest D flawless
   diamond to ever come to market.

30:02.008 --> 30:06.262
It is the largest emerald cut
      ever offered at auction.

30:06.304 --> 30:08.306
But the truth is there are

30:08.348 --> 30:10.850
a lot of diamonds waiting
            for the company

30:10.892 --> 30:15.814
to have a good reason
     to have a miraculous find,

30:15.855 --> 30:19.692
and then someone-- let's say...

30:19.734 --> 30:22.695
someone with a skill set
