50:20.434 --> 50:22.561
I remember him
        as being scary.  

50:22.602 --> 50:26.023
That is one of
      the most incredible stories.

50:26.064 --> 50:28.233
From shoveling
        Tracy Hall's driveway

50:28.275 --> 50:30.402
to marrying an Oppenheimer.

50:30.444 --> 50:33.238
I did think subsequently,
         "What if I had left

50:33.280 --> 50:35.907
just a little bit more ice
    on that pavement?" 

50:35.949 --> 50:37.117
Really?

50:37.159 --> 50:38.618
Well, would we have had

50:38.660 --> 50:39.911
another couple of decades

50:39.953 --> 50:41.246
without synthesized diamond?

50:42.247 --> 50:45.042
dramatic music

50:47.169 --> 50:49.379
I think the fact that

50:49.421 --> 50:51.757
the very top brass at De Beers

50:51.798 --> 50:54.593
sat in a room with you
        and signed a release,

50:54.634 --> 50:57.929
it's a sign
       of incredible weakness.

51:00.599 --> 51:04.603
Compared to five years ago,
      there would be no interview.

51:04.644 --> 51:06.521
There would never be
             an interview.

51:06.563 --> 51:08.398
There's a lot of reasons
               for that.

51:08.440 --> 51:10.067
One of them is,

51:10.108 --> 51:13.445
if synthetic diamond jewelry
   ever takes a big market share--

51:13.487 --> 51:15.614
which I think
        it very well could--

51:15.655 --> 51:17.699
then it would end up
        like cultured pearls.

51:17.741 --> 51:19.868
No one would remember
     there was ever a difference

51:19.910 --> 51:22.579
between cultured diamonds
     and not-cultured diamonds.

51:22.621 --> 51:25.415
I don't even bother
        keeping them separate

51:25.457 --> 51:27.876
in my jewelry boxes.

51:42.390 --> 51:45.519
If you want people
    to really absorb information,

51:45.560 --> 51:47.813
you need to be able
         to tell it to them

51:47.854 --> 51:50.190
in a way that is memorable.

51:50.232 --> 51:52.150
That's the definition
          of a storyteller.

51:54.736 --> 51:57.656
Stories are the only way
            in today's world

51:57.697 --> 52:02.285
people can absorb information
            in any depth.

52:02.327 --> 52:05.956
In the old days,
     it was more classic marketing.

52:05.997 --> 52:10.669
You know, I could buy NBC, CBS,
     and you all saw it in a week.

52:10.710 --> 52:13.130
But now it's-it's more core.

52:13.171 --> 52:15.173
You need to take a step back.

52:15.215 --> 52:17.676
It's not about myths.
          It's about truth.

52:17.717 --> 52:22.514
And truth is a good thing
    if your story is a good one.

52:22.556 --> 52:24.808
gentle music

52:27.853 --> 52:29.688
Actually, here in Botswana,

52:29.729 --> 52:32.023
the world's leading producer
              of diamonds,

52:32.065 --> 52:35.694
there's a huge positive benefit
   created by the natural diamond.

52:43.285 --> 52:45.370
You know, sometimes
          synthetic producers

52:45.412 --> 52:47.080
try and position their product

52:47.122 --> 52:49.708
as somehow an ethical
     or environmental alternative.

52:49.749 --> 52:52.043
They say, "Oh, we don't make
       a hole in the ground."

52:52.085 --> 52:55.338
And you're right, we do make
       a big hole in the ground.

52:55.380 --> 52:57.883
It's about
         two kilometers across,

52:57.924 --> 53:00.093
in a country the size of France,

53:00.135 --> 53:03.513
with nothing around it
             but scrubland.

53:03.555 --> 53:05.265
You can look at that
            in two ways.

53:05.307 --> 53:06.933
You can look at that hole
              and say,

53:06.975 --> 53:08.393
"There's a big hole
           in the ground,"

53:08.435 --> 53:11.396
or you can look
        in that hole and think,

53:11.438 --> 53:15.066
how lucky the people
            of Botswana were

53:15.108 --> 53:19.404
to have this two-kilometer
     bit of land in an area that--

53:19.446 --> 53:21.072
what were they gonna do with it?

53:21.114 --> 53:23.074
Have like ten cows?

53:25.285 --> 53:27.871
And in that hole has been

53:27.913 --> 53:31.374
this extraordinary
      transformation of a country

53:31.416 --> 53:34.002
from four miles of tarred road
              to 4,000

53:34.044 --> 53:35.879
because of that hole
           in the ground.

53:35.921 --> 53:39.090
A doctor for every 50,000 people
          before diamonds.

53:39.132 --> 53:41.176
Now a doctor for every 300.

53:41.218 --> 53:44.054
Hospitals, free education. Why?

53:44.095 --> 53:46.765
It's-it's that hole
           in the ground.

53:49.517 --> 53:52.145
De Beers is an African company.

53:52.187 --> 53:55.649
A lot of us may be based
     in London, but the deep ethos

53:55.690 --> 53:58.652
of our operations
       has Africa at its core.

53:59.945 --> 54:02.572
And there's nothing
      more important to an African

54:02.614 --> 54:05.325
than their environment--
 in particular, their wildlife--

54:05.367 --> 54:08.328
and you need to protect that,
                as well.

54:08.370 --> 54:10.538
uplifting music

54:13.333 --> 54:14.960
You know, if I could bring

54:15.001 --> 54:16.962
every American
     engagement ring consumer here

54:17.003 --> 54:20.966
to see with their own eyes
           what diamonds do,

54:21.007 --> 54:24.386
they would never buy anything
     but-but a natural diamond.

54:24.427 --> 54:26.721
You'd actually say,
          "Geez, you know,

54:26.763 --> 54:29.224
why would you
        synthesize something

54:29.266 --> 54:31.810
when it could do such harm
        to-to this country?"

54:39.609 --> 54:41.945
The story is extraordinarily

54:41.987 --> 54:46.324
inspiring and has the great
     convenience of being true.

54:46.366 --> 54:49.577
And you show me another
       two-kilometer bit of...

54:49.619 --> 54:52.664
of the world that has done that.

55:12.350 --> 55:14.102
I want to take
     this problem of synthetics

55:14.144 --> 55:16.104
to a whole other level.

55:16.146 --> 55:19.065
We're now living
          in a world of...

55:19.107 --> 55:21.735
gender equality.

55:21.776 --> 55:26.239
Are diamonds under threat
 not because of synthetics only--

55:26.281 --> 55:28.158
although synthetics
          brings it down--

55:28.199 --> 55:29.826
because of
       the whole question of,

55:29.868 --> 55:32.037
what is the relationship
    between the man and the woman

55:32.078 --> 55:34.372
in the 21st century?

55:35.749 --> 55:39.377
Why is she receiving the gift
            and not him?

55:39.419 --> 55:41.629
What's going on here?

55:41.671 --> 55:44.799
I could talk about the idea
            of, you know,

55:44.841 --> 55:47.010
uh, anthropological studies
              that show

55:47.052 --> 55:49.679
that the woman has the babies
 and, because she has the babies,

55:49.721 --> 55:51.556
she wants the man
        to make a commitment

55:51.598 --> 55:54.309
and know that he's gonna
         support her. Okay.

55:54.351 --> 55:56.394
But we live in
        a modern world today

55:56.436 --> 55:58.563
where women may be earning
           more than men.

55:58.605 --> 56:01.733
She may not need him
            or want him.

56:01.775 --> 56:03.860
We switch jobs
       every couple of years.

56:03.902 --> 56:07.530
Maybe we're gonna switch,
    uh, partners every few years.

56:07.572 --> 56:09.908
Our-our society is changing.

56:09.949 --> 56:13.078
And so the role of the diamond
           is under threat

56:13.119 --> 56:16.373
because the role of the woman
    and the man is under threat.

56:16.414 --> 56:21.336
But every day,
   millennials are getting older.

56:21.378 --> 56:24.089
Their clocks are ticking.

56:24.130 --> 56:26.299
Their desire to procreate,

56:26.341 --> 56:28.468
whether it's genetic
            or otherwise

56:28.510 --> 56:32.263
or whether it's, uh, uh,
        Darwinian, is there.

56:32.305 --> 56:35.058
What's going to happen?

56:35.100 --> 56:40.105
Does the diamond play a role
   in cementing the relationship?

56:40.146 --> 56:43.233
Does the woman
        still want a diamond?

56:43.274 --> 56:46.194
And if so, why?

56:53.410 --> 56:55.912
I-I did. Yeah.

56:55.954 --> 57:00.792
I-I grew a diamond
       for my former fiancée.

57:00.834 --> 57:02.335
Wait, so what's the story there?

57:02.377 --> 57:04.379
Um...

57:04.421 --> 57:06.965
I grew a diamond
     and had it cut and polished

57:07.006 --> 57:10.885
and, uh, had it set in a setting

57:10.927 --> 57:13.680
and proposed to her with it.

57:14.848 --> 57:16.599
- And?

57:16.641 --> 57:18.810
I think she was unimpressed.

57:18.852 --> 57:21.062
What does that mean?

57:21.104 --> 57:22.730
It was too small.

57:22.772 --> 57:24.399
It was half a carat.

57:24.441 --> 57:27.610
-What did she say?
               -Um...

57:28.736 --> 57:30.363
...that she wanted a bigger one.

57:36.870 --> 57:40.206
Ladies and gentlemen,
            dear colleagues,

57:40.248 --> 57:45.253
my name is D-Dusan Simic,
   and, uh, I'll talk today about

57:45.295 --> 57:48.506
my invention, my patent.

57:56.055 --> 57:58.433
It will ensure that we will have

57:58.475 --> 58:01.686
two completely different
              products

58:01.728 --> 58:04.689
that cannot hurt each other.

58:07.317 --> 58:09.694
Yeah, yeah, yeah, it is.
         It was a decision.

58:09.736 --> 58:12.739
Right now, I'm closing the lab

58:12.780 --> 58:16.075
and I'm going, uh, to do
       other things, you know.

58:16.117 --> 58:18.828
It-it was nonsense to have a lab

58:18.870 --> 58:23.124
that it doesn't bring,
     it doesn't bring any money.

58:23.166 --> 58:24.501
I really believe in this.

58:24.542 --> 58:26.753
I mean, it could be
        a solution, you know.

58:26.794 --> 58:28.546
upbeat music

1:00:06.686 --> 1:00:08.980
Can I ask a dumb question?

1:00:33.921 --> 1:00:36.507
Of course. Of course.

1:00:56.402 --> 1:00:59.197
Uh, this brings
       the presentations to...

1:01:07.830 --> 1:01:10.541
-Come on, I know all about you.
      -Okay. Yeah, yeah, yeah.

1:01:19.258 --> 1:01:20.677
-You-you have a power...
      -I'll do a deal with you.

1:01:20.718 --> 1:01:21.844
You have the power...

1:01:21.886 --> 1:01:22.679
I have the power
          to make it work.

1:01:22.720 --> 1:01:23.971
...to make it work.

1:01:24.889 --> 1:01:26.474
Yes?

1:01:43.449 --> 1:01:45.118
contemplative music

1:02:00.758 --> 1:02:02.885
And action.

1:02:08.099 --> 1:02:10.852
At De Beers, everything you do,

1:02:10.893 --> 1:02:13.271
if the person
         who owns your diamond

1:02:13.312 --> 1:02:15.440
sees anything
        that makes them unhappy,

1:02:15.481 --> 1:02:17.275
is the wrong thing to do.

1:02:17.316 --> 1:02:20.862
They have to feel proud
       of-of-of that diamond.

1:02:20.903 --> 1:02:23.531
That bit is, like,
           the sacrosanct.

1:02:23.573 --> 1:02:26.284
You must protect them.

1:02:26.325 --> 1:02:28.286
You don't want people
        who question things.

1:02:28.327 --> 1:02:29.871
Those aren't good consumers.

1:02:29.912 --> 1:02:31.706
They question
        how many of their...

1:02:31.748 --> 1:02:33.583
"Are all of these real?

1:02:33.624 --> 1:02:37.128
Well, how I know for sure?"

1:02:37.170 --> 1:02:38.713
Then they're gonna start
        to ask questions about--

1:02:38.755 --> 1:02:40.631
what are the differences?

1:02:44.302 --> 1:02:45.803
I don't hate De Beers.

1:02:45.845 --> 1:02:47.305
It's not a personal grudge.

1:02:47.346 --> 1:02:49.682
It has nothing to do
       with my career, per se,

1:02:49.724 --> 1:02:51.768
like, you know,
        anybody's annoyed me

1:02:51.809 --> 1:02:53.144
at any point in the past

1:02:53.186 --> 1:02:55.813
or being the only woman
            in the room.

1:02:55.855 --> 1:02:57.857
I-I have no skin in the game.

1:02:59.525 --> 1:03:04.489
It's just that I'm interested
 in what they're actually doing.

1:03:04.530 --> 1:03:06.991
And I think, if you look closer,

1:03:07.033 --> 1:03:10.286
it's never really
      what you thought you saw.

1:03:12.747 --> 1:03:14.665
And in this case,
            you're assuming

1:03:14.707 --> 1:03:17.293
the mixing scandal
           was ever a problem

1:03:17.335 --> 1:03:19.337
for the people
        claiming it's a problem.

1:03:19.378 --> 1:03:21.255
Because they're also

1:03:21.297 --> 1:03:25.343
the ones putting the most money
    and quietly the most manpower

1:03:25.384 --> 1:03:29.347
into growing them in labs.

1:03:31.307 --> 1:03:35.353
So, a lie about a lie
      about a lie about a lie.

1:03:35.394 --> 1:03:37.104
Delightful.

1:03:37.146 --> 1:03:40.149
The diamond jewelry industry
        is set for a shake-up

1:03:40.191 --> 1:03:43.027
after global diamond giant
         De Beers announced

1:03:43.069 --> 1:03:45.696
it planned to sell diamonds
       grown in a laboratory.

1:03:45.738 --> 1:03:49.200
After years of
     criticizing lab-made diamonds,

1:03:49.242 --> 1:03:51.702
the world's largest
        diamond miner, De Beers,

1:03:51.744 --> 1:03:53.371
will now sell them.

1:03:53.412 --> 1:03:57.208
Of course they were
    working on growing their own.

1:03:57.250 --> 1:04:00.545
De Beers never sold a diamond--
         they sold an idea--

1:04:00.586 --> 1:04:02.713
and this is just a new idea.

1:04:02.755 --> 1:04:04.924
The Lightbox brand is bringing

1:04:04.966 --> 1:04:08.386
the synthesized product
            in a way that is

1:04:08.427 --> 1:04:09.804
honest about what it is

1:04:09.846 --> 1:04:12.682
but, equally importantly,
           what it isn't.

1:04:12.723 --> 1:04:14.392
The difference is that,

1:04:14.433 --> 1:04:16.519
while a natural diamond is made
       over billions of years,

1:04:16.561 --> 1:04:18.229
comes from deep in the ground,

1:04:18.271 --> 1:04:22.149
a lab-grown diamond is
     literally made in a factory

1:04:22.191 --> 1:04:24.485
over a period
         of about two weeks.

1:04:24.527 --> 1:04:26.737
It's something less precious.

1:04:26.779 --> 1:04:28.239
Maybe for travel jewelry.

1:04:28.281 --> 1:04:30.032
It's a nice thing, huh?

1:04:30.074 --> 1:04:33.828
It's... you know, you see
    a sparkly blue or pink stone,

1:04:33.870 --> 1:04:36.873
it's pretty, and it's
      very inexpensive to make.

1:04:36.914 --> 1:04:39.000
Consumer research tells us
          that women prefer

1:04:39.041 --> 1:04:41.210
natural diamonds
      for life's big occasions

1:04:41.252 --> 1:04:43.421
like an engagement ring
         or a wedding band,

1:04:43.462 --> 1:04:46.048
but these are perfect for all
     of other life's occasions.

1:04:46.090 --> 1:04:48.175
If you lose it,
        don't worry so much,

1:04:48.217 --> 1:04:49.927
'cause it's not very expensive.

1:04:49.969 --> 1:04:52.179
It's not a memorable thing
       that 30 years from now

1:04:52.221 --> 1:04:54.557
you're going to be,
        you know, cherishing.

1:04:54.599 --> 1:04:56.767
You're not gonna pass it on
          to your children.

1:04:56.809 --> 1:04:58.603
But there's a lot
        of jewelry like that,

1:04:58.644 --> 1:05:00.605
and there's nothing wrong
              with it.

1:05:00.646 --> 1:05:02.315
Oh, yeah, really?

1:05:02.356 --> 1:05:03.983
After shitting on it
           for ten years,

1:05:04.025 --> 1:05:05.693
you want to get into it?
             All right.

1:05:05.735 --> 1:05:07.153
I think where it came from is

1:05:07.194 --> 1:05:08.988
they want to cut out
       all the people like me.

1:05:09.030 --> 1:05:11.032
They want to cut out all
         the people that are

1:05:11.073 --> 1:05:13.284
creating new diamonds
     by undercutting the market.

1:05:13.326 --> 1:05:15.411
The gemstone giant De Beers

1:05:15.453 --> 1:05:18.789
is building a $94 million dollar
        plant there in Gresham.

1:05:18.831 --> 1:05:21.083
The laboratory-made
            stones produced

1:05:21.125 --> 1:05:24.253
will be up to 90% less expensive
          than natural stones.

1:05:24.295 --> 1:05:26.047
At that point,
           you have to assume

1:05:26.088 --> 1:05:28.132
